Female films and TV practitioners under the aegis of Women in Films & Television International (WIFTI) have sought the support and partnership of the Ooni of Ife, Adeyeye Ogunwusi ahead of the 2022 summit. This is coming after the WIFTI appointed Ascend Studios Foundation (ASF) as the implementing partner for the WIFTI Summit 2022, which is being held in Africa for the first time. The summit tagged “Telling Unique Stories with Film, Music, and Dance,” aims to incorporate the aspects of film, music, and dance to advance the funding, creation, and distribution of stories that reflect the thriving, socially aware film culture around the world. On his acceptance of the partnership, the imperial majesty Ogunwusi Adeyeye expressed his support for causes related to women empowerment, especially Nigerian women.   Sean Dampte speaks on upcoming album     Rudeboy meets twin brothers who won PSquare jackets     Rising Juju act Seyi Michael releases 5th album ‘Ijo…   - Advertisement - “While not wanting to lose out with the current situation of things, we must continue to cherish our cultural heritage and values, which were handed over to us by our ancestors,” Oba Ogunwusi said. To achieve this, multicultural diversity in film, music, and dance will be established to serve reflection of cultures of arts, stories, and values. The summit will train thousands, have a significant international presence, and host attendees, partners, and film offices from all over the world. It will feature an incredible line-up of A-list film/TV actors, musicians, dance players, as well as international and local organisations interested in the creative economy. ASF, led by Inya Lawal, is working with WIFTI, led by Helene Granqvist, Women in Film and TV Africa (WIFTA), Forum of Women in Film and TV (FWIFT) led by Joke Silva to build alliances and partnerships with local and international organisations.